<B>Conformance=20
                  to the OSD</B> ::.</SPAN> </TD></TR>
              <TR>
                <TD bgColor=3D#ffffff>
                  <P>(This section is not part of the Open Source=20
                  Definition.)</P>
                  <P>We think the Open Source Definition captures what =
the great=20
                  majority of the software community originally meant, =
and still=20
                  mean, by the term "Open Source". However, the term has =
become=20
                  widely used and its meaning has lost some precision. =
The=20
                  <STRONG>OSI Certified</STRONG> mark is OSI's way of =
certifying=20
                  that the license under which the software is =
distributed=20
                  conforms to the OSD; the generic term "Open Source" =
cannot=20
                  provide that assurance, but we still encourage use of =
the term=20
                  "Open Source" to mean conformance to the OSD. For =
information=20
                  about the <STRONG>OSI Certified</STRONG> mark, and for =
a list=20
                  of licenses that OSI has approved as conforming to the =
OSD,=20
                  see the OSD <A=20
                  =
href=3D"http://opensource.org/docs/certification_mark.php">Certification =

                  Mark =
page</A>.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!-- =
end sidebox --><!-- section seperator -->
