                    <TR>
                      <TD bgColor=3D#ffffff><!--INSERT TRANSLATION =
HERE-->
                        <H1>The Open Source Definition</H1>
                        <P>Version 1.9</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I>The indented, italicized sections below =
appear=20
                          as annotations to the Open Source Definition =
(OSD) and=20
                          are <B>not</B> a part of the OSD. A plain =
version of=20
                          the OSD without annotations can be found <A=20
                          =
href=3D"http://opensource.org/docs/definition_plain.php">here</A>.</I></P=
>
                          <P><I>A printable version of this annotated =
page is=20
                          available <A=20
                          =
href=3D"http://opensource.org/docs/def_print.php">here</A></I>.=20
                          </FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
                        <H2>Introduction</H2>
                        <P>Open source doesn't just mean access to the =
source=20
                        code. The distribution terms of open-source =
software=20
                        must comply with the following criteria: <A =
name=3D1>
                        <H3>1. Free Redistribution</H3></A>
                        <P>The license shall not restrict any party from =
selling=20
                        or giving away the software as a component of an =

                        aggregate software distribution containing =
programs from=20
                        several different sources. The license shall not =
require=20
                        a royalty or other fee for such sale.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> By constraining the =
license to=20
                          require free redistribution, we eliminate the=20
                          temptation to throw away many long-term gains =
in order=20
                          to make a few short-term sales dollars. If we =
didn't=20
                          do this, there would be lots of pressure for=20
                          cooperators to defect.</I> =
</FONT></P></BLOCKQUOTE><A=20
                        name=3D2>
                        <H3>2. Source Code</H3></A>
                        <P>The program must include source code, and =
must allow=20
                        distribution in source code as well as compiled =
form.=20
                        Where some form of a product is not distributed =
with=20
                        source code, there must be a well-publicized =
means of=20
                        obtaining the source code for no more than a =
reasonable=20
                        reproduction cost=96preferably, downloading via =
the=20
                        Internet without charge. The source code must be =
the=20
                        preferred form in which a programmer would =
modify the=20
                        program. Deliberately obfuscated source code is =
not=20
                        allowed. Intermediate forms such as the output =
of a=20
                        preprocessor or translator are not allowed.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> We require access to=20
                          un-obfuscated source code because you can't =
evolve=20
                          programs without modifying them. Since our =
purpose is=20
                          to make evolution easy, we require that =
modification=20
                          be made easy.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A =
name=3D3>
                        <H3>3. Derived Works</H3></A>
                        <P>The license must allow modifications and =
derived=20
                        works, and must allow them to be distributed =
under the=20
                        same terms as the license of the original =
software.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> The mere ability to =
read=20
                          source isn't enough to support independent =
peer review=20
                          and rapid evolutionary selection. For rapid =
evolution=20
                          to happen, people need to be able to =
experiment with=20
                          and redistribute=20
                        modifications.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A =
name=3D4>
                        <H3>4. Integrity of The Author's Source =
Code</H3></A>
                        <P>The license may restrict source-code from =
being=20
                        distributed in modified form <EM>only</EM> if =
the=20
                        license allows the distribution of "patch files" =
with=20
                        the source code for the purpose of modifying the =
program=20
                        at build time. The license must explicitly =
permit=20
                        distribution of software built from modified =
source=20
                        code. The license may require derived works to =
carry a=20
                        different name or version number from the =
original=20
                        software.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> Encouraging lots of=20
                          improvement is a good thing, but users have a =
right to=20
                          know who is responsible for the software they =
are=20
                          using. Authors and maintainers have reciprocal =
right=20
                          to know what they're being asked to support =
and=20
                          protect their reputations.</I></P>
                          <P><I>Accordingly, an open-source license =
<B>must</B>=20
                          guarantee that source be readily available, =
but=20
                          <B>may</B> require that it be distributed as =
pristine=20
                          base sources plus patches. In this way, =
"unofficial"=20
                          changes can be made available but readily=20
                          distinguished from the base=20
                        source.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A name=3D5>
                        <H3>5. No Discrimination Against Persons or=20
                        Groups</H3></A>
                        <P>The license must not discriminate against any =
person=20
                        or group of persons.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> In order to get the =
maximum=20
                          benefit from the process, the maximum =
diversity of=20
                          persons and groups should be equally eligible =
to=20
                          contribute to open sources. Therefore we =
forbid any=20
                          open-source license from locking anybody out =
of the=20
                          process.</I></P>
                          <P><I>Some countries, including the United =
States,=20
                          have export restrictions for certain types of=20
                          software. An OSD-conformant license may warn =
licensees=20
                          of applicable restrictions and remind them =
that they=20
                          are obliged to obey the law; however, it may =
not=20
                          incorporate such restrictions=20
                        itself.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A name=3D6>
                        <H3>6. No Discrimination Against Fields of=20
                        Endeavor</H3></A>
                        <P>The license must not restrict anyone from =
making use=20
                        of the program in a specific field of endeavor. =
For=20
                        example, it may not restrict the program from =
being used=20
                        in a business, or from being used for genetic=20
                        research.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> The major intention of =
this=20
                          clause is to prohibit license traps that =
prevent open=20
                          source from being used commercially. We want=20
                          commercial users to join our community, not =
feel=20
                          excluded from =
it.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A name=3D7>
                        <H3>7. Distribution of License</H3></A>
                        <P>The rights attached to the program must apply =
to all=20
                        to whom the program is redistributed without the =
need=20
                        for execution of an additional license by those=20
                        parties.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> This clause is =
intended to=20
                          forbid closing up software by indirect means =
such as=20
                          requiring a non-disclosure=20
                        agreement.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A =
name=3D8>
                        <H3>8. License Must Not Be Specific to a=20
Product</H3></A>
                        <P>The rights attached to the program must not =
depend on=20
                        the program's being part of a particular =
software=20
                        distribution. If the program is extracted from =
that=20
                        distribution and used or distributed within the =
terms of=20
                        the program's license, all parties to whom the =
program=20
                        is redistributed should have the same rights as =
those=20
                        that are granted in conjunction with the =
original=20
                        software distribution.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> This clause forecloses =
yet=20
                          another class of license=20
                        traps.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A name=3D9>
                        <H3>9. License Must Not Restrict Other =
Software</H3></A>
                        <P>The license must not place restrictions on =
other=20
                        software that is distributed along with the =
licensed=20
                        software. For example, the license must not =
insist that=20
                        all other programs distributed on the same =
medium must=20
                        be open-source software.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> Distributors of =
open-source=20
                          software have the right to make their own =
choices=20
                          about their own software.</I></P>
                          <P><I>Yes, the GPL is conformant with this=20
                          requirement. Software linked with GPLed =
libraries only=20
                          inherits the GPL if it forms a single work, =
not any=20
                          software with which they are merely=20
                          distributed.</I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><A =
name=3D10>
                        <H3>*10. License Must Be =
Technology-Neutral</H3></A>
                        <P>No provision of the license may be predicated =
on any=20
                        individual technology or style of interface.</P>
                        <BLOCKQUOTE><FONT size=3D-1>
                          <P><I><B>Rationale:</B> This provision is =
aimed=20
                          specifically at licenses which require an =
explicit=20
                          gesture of assent in order to establish a =
contract=20
                          between licensor and licensee. Provisions =
mandating=20
                          so-called "click-wrap" may conflict with =
important=20
                          methods of software distribution such as FTP =
download,=20
                          CD-ROM anthologies, and web mirroring; such =
provisions=20
                          may also hinder code re-use. Conformant =
licenses must=20
                          allow for the possibility that (a) =
redistribution of=20
                          the software will take place over non-Web =
channels=20
                          that do not support click-wrapping of the =
download,=20
                          and that (b) the covered code (or re-used =
portions of=20
                          covered code) may run in a non-GUI environment =
that=20
                          cannot support popup dialogues.=20
                        </I></P></FONT></BLOCKQUOTE><!--END TRANSLATION =
HERE---></TD></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><!-- =
end story --><BR><!-- story --></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
